cc:Work.dc:title: Tapping Fiber-Optic Cables on the Cheap

text.tspan: Tapping Fiber-Optic Cables on the Cheap

flowRoot.flowPara: Fiber optic cables are the backbone of International communication. Given the administrative and financial advantage of oceanic over land-based cable routes, most traffic between countries is delivered by the sea.
With the Snowden revelations, it became known that nation-state actors tap oceanic fiber optic cables.
We investigated within 6 weeks and a budget of 20 Euro what techniques can be used for intercepting low-speed fiber-optic communication.
The Method
Cutting a cable interrupts the connection and the fracture can be easily measured and located by the cable operator.

We had to find a method that will leave the cable intact but still leak enough light to the outside to be detectable. Testing showed that two types of bends work: Micro- and Macro-bending. With Micro-bending a dimple is made in the cable so that a fraction of the light is reflected with a high angle of incidence through the calding. The same principle holds macro-bending, but that the whole cable is bent.
Micro-Bend
Macro-bend
Carefully make a small opening in the inner fiber using sandpaper.
Bend the cable and check if some of the light comes out.
Tape the phototransistor to the cable and measure its value using a simple pull-up circuit.
Record the measurements and analyze them.
Remove the outer shielding using a utility knife.
Building a low-cost proof-of-concept

Using two commercial fiber-optic transceivers, we made and programmed an optical link. Building a small lightproof chamber in which we macro-bend the cable, we are able to read the communication between two end points with the use of a photo detector.

The working prototype is in front of you. All components can be bought online, the total value of the interceptor is less than 5 Euro. When a battery, a water-tight container and memory storage are added, then a very cheap and self-sufficient underwater tapper can be constructed.
Conclusion
This proof of concept shows that low speed fiber-topic tapping is possible for as little as 5 Euro. Communications over fiber are not immune to tapping, and should also be encrypted.
Doing it on land is one thing. In the spring we will go diving and tap a cable underwater....
